result.execSummary:
Henry L Wiechers was found not guilty on all charges in this case. These charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Henry L Wiechers is presumed innocent.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

9:07 AM Defendant Henry L Wiechers in court.  Attorney William George Weiland in court for Henry L Wiechers.  Attorney Rose Yanke in court for State of Wisconsin. 

9:10 AM  Jury is brought in and sworn.  20 jurors are called to the jury box.  
9:17 AM  Court addresses the jurors.  Attorney Yanke introduces herself and potential witnesses to the jury. Attorney Weiland introduces himself and potential witnesses to the jury.  9:18 AM  Court commences with voir dire.   9:22 AM  Attorney Yanke commences with voir dire.  9:28 AM  Sidebar.  9:31 AM  Court advises the jurors of the stipulations reached by the parties regarding the blood draw, chain of custody and results of the blood draw.  9:32 AM Attorney Yanke continues with voir dire. 9:33 AM  Attorney Weiland commences with voir dire.  

9:38 AM  Court instructs the jury and counsel commence with strikes.    9:45 AM  12 jurors are chosen, sworn and seated.  

9:48 AM  Jury leaves. Attorney Weiland bring a motion for mistrial and makes his argument.  Court denies the motion.  Attorney Weiland may draft a curative instruction.  Court places the sidebar issue on the record.

10:03 AM  Court reconvenes with the jury present.  10:05 AM  Attorney Yanke gives her opening statement.  Attorney Weiland will have his opening statement in his case in chief.

10:10 AM  Officer Allie Eckes is sworn and questioned by Attorney Yanke. Testifies to employment, training and education. Testifies to being dispatched to the Seven Star Motel. Testifies to observing a male subject in the driver seat with an empty bottle of alcohol.  Testifies that the vehicle was equipped with an IDD device. Testifies to her observations of the defendant in the vehicle. Testifies that defendant performed the HGN field sobriety tests. Testifies that defendant failed the test.  Testifies to placing defendant under arrest.  10:22 AM  Cross-examination by Attorney Weiland.  Questions witness regarding her observations when arriving at the Seven Star Motel.  Exhibit 1 is marked and identified by the witness.  Exhibit 1 is received and published to the jury.  Questions witness at length regarding the use of the IID device.  10:34 AM  Re-direct by Attorney Yanke.   10:36 AM  Re-cross by Attorney Weiland.  

10:37 AM  Officer Brody Erickson is sworn and questioned by Attorney Yanke.  Testifies to employment, training and education.  Testifies to being dispatched to the Seven Star Motel.  Witness identifies the defendant in the courtroom.  10:43 AM  Cross-examination by Attorney Weiland.  Re-direct by Attorney Yanke.  Re-cross by Attorney Weiland.  Re-direct by Attorney Yanke.

10:47 AM  Jury leaves. Court takes a break. 

10:48 AM  State rests.  Attorney Weiland brings a motion to dismiss and makes his argument.  Attorney Yanke argues in opposition. 10:52 AM  Court takes a break.  

11:07 AM  Back on the record without the jury present.  Court denies the motion to dismiss.  11:12 AM  Court enters into a colloquy with the defendant regarding his right to testify.  

11:22 AM  Back on the record with the jury present.  Attorney Weiland gives his opening statement.  

11:25 AM  Officer Eckes re-takes the witness stand and is questioned by Attorney Weiland. Questions witness regarding the video on her dash camera.  Questions witness regarding brake lights being illuminated on the vehicle.  11:28 AM Cross-examination by Attorney Yanke. Re-cross by Attorney Weiland. Re-cross by Attorney Yanke.  Re-direct by Attorney Weiland. 

11:34 AM  Devon Wiechers is sworn and questioned by Attorney Weiland. Testifies that defendant is his father.  Testifies that defendant was sitting in his car and he started the car to keep the car warm.  11:38 AM  Cross-examination by Attorney Yanke.  11:40 AM  Sidebar.  11:42 AM  Attorney Yanke continues her cross-examination.  Questions witness at length regarding the specifics of the defendant's vehicle.  11:47 AM  Re-direct by Attorney Weiland. Re-cross by Attorney Yanke.  Re-direct by Attorney Weiland. Defense rests.  State does not have any rebuttal witnesses.

11:50 AM  Jury leaves.  Court places the sidebar issue on the record.  11:55 AM  Court takes a break.

1:13 PM  Back on the record without the jury present.  Court and counsel review the jury instructions and verdicts.  

1:32 PM  Back on the record with the jury present.  Court instructs the jury.  

1:47 PM  Attorney Yanke gives her closing argument.  1:52 PM  Attorney Weiland gives his closing argument.  1:58 PM  Attorney Yanke gives rebuttal argument.

2:02 PM   Court gives final instruction to the jury.

2:07 PM  Bailiffs are sworn.  Jury leaves to deliberate.  

2:50 PM  On the record with the jury present.  Jury has reached a verdict.  Count 1. Not guilty.  Count 2.  Not guilty.   Court polls the jury. 

2:53 PM  Attorney Weiland moves to dismiss the case and enter the Verdicts. Court grants.
